# Schema Evolution Standards

This document defines standards for evolving data schemas while maintaining backward and forward compatibility.

---

## Compatibility Types

| Type | Definition | When Required |
|------|-----------|---------------|
| Backward compatible | New schema can read old data | Always for storage schemas |
| Forward compatible | Old schema can read new data | When consumers can't update simultaneously |
| Full compatible | Both backward and forward | Critical shared schemas |

---

## Safe Changes (Backward Compatible)

| Change | Safe? | Notes |
|--------|-------|-------|
| Add optional field with default | Yes | Old data will use default |
| Add new enum value | Yes | Old readers ignore unknown values |
| Widen numeric type (int32 -> int64) | Yes | No data loss |
| Add new table/topic | Yes | No impact on existing |

## Unsafe Changes (Breaking)

| Change | Safe? | Migration Required |
|--------|-------|--------------------|
| Remove field | No | Deprecation period first |
| Rename field | No | Add new + deprecate old |
| Change field type | No | New field + migration |
| Make optional field required | No | Backfill defaults first |
| Remove enum value | No | Verify no data uses it |

---

## Migration Strategy

### For Breaking Changes

1. **Add new field** alongside the old field
2. **Dual-write** both old and new fields during transition
3. **Migrate consumers** to read from new field
4. **Verify** no consumers read old field
5. **Remove** old field after deprecation period

```python
# Phase 1: Add new field, dual-write
class UserEvent:
    name: str           # Deprecated: use display_name
    display_name: str   # New field

    def __init__(self, name: str):
        self.name = name
        self.display_name = name  # Dual-write

# Phase 2: After all consumers migrated
class UserEvent:
    display_name: str   # Only new field
```

### Version Numbering

```
v{major}.{minor}

major: Breaking changes
minor: Backward-compatible additions
```

---

## Schema Registry

### Required for Each Schema

| Field | Description |
|-------|-------------|
| name | Unique schema identifier |
| version | Current version number |
| compatibility | backward / forward / full |
| fields | Complete field definitions |
| owner | Team responsible |
| consumers | Known downstream consumers |
| last_updated | Date of last change |

---

## Deprecation Process

| Phase | Duration | Actions |
|-------|----------|---------|
| Announcement | Week 0 | Notify consumers, log deprecation warnings |
| Dual support | Weeks 1-4 | Both old and new schemas work |
| Soft removal | Weeks 5-8 | Old schema returns warnings |
| Hard removal | Week 9+ | Old schema returns errors |

---

## Testing

- [ ] Schema compatibility checked in CI (e.g., Avro compatibility checker)
- [ ] Old data can be read by new code
- [ ] New data can be read by previous version of code (if forward compatible)
- [ ] Migration scripts are tested with production-like data volumes
- [ ] Rollback procedure is tested
